    <p>Every Chinese textbook starts with 你好 (nǐ hǎo) — and then real life happens. According to a <a href="https://www.sinosplice.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Sinosplice</a> survey of Chinese language usage, native speakers use 你好 in fewer than <strong>20% of daily greetings</strong>. The rest of the time, they use a rich variety of context-dependent phrases that textbooks rarely teach. This guide covers <strong>30 essential greetings</strong> organized by situation, so you sound natural from day one.</p>

    <div style="margin: 2rem 0; padding: 1.2rem; background: #f9fafb; border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">
      <div style="font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.85rem; color: #374151; margin-bottom: 0.8rem; text-align: center;">How Chinese Speakers Actually Greet (Usage Frequency)</div>
